{
  "doc_id": "26101",
  "text": "We started by extending the modeling language BlenX and the associated computational framework BetaWB with general distributions. BlenX allows including in the same model different levels of (qualitative) abstraction and so it is well suited to be tested in an environment with general distributions. Here we described the general ideas underlying BlenX and its extension in a tutorial fashion, pointing the interested reader to [CITATION_1] . Then, we described three examples that present an increasing complexity. The examples resulted sensitive to variances of reaction occurrence times as non-linearity and complexity of the system increase. Moreover, the extension presented can help in providing better matching between wet-lab experiments and in-silico results.",
